metadata.name: Sixty# #18
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: PXL #393
metadata.description:
PXL is an exploration of video synthesis, each pixel containing 4 cells phasing between two values. This effect creates all sorts of interesting effects when scaled up, so enjoy the completely unique effect your optical illusion generates.

There is a 5% chance to generate a wave glitch in your pattern.

Color palettes:
80% Normal (Randomly Generated)
10% Monochrome
5% RGB
5% CMYK

Press 's' to save a png
Press 'm' to save a 10s mp4 (can take up to 2m to render)

metadata.name: KINJO! #481
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

metadata.name: Protein Pelt #453
metadata.description:
An incorrectly placed decimal point led to this pattern. A good friend told me it reminded them of protein structures, I found them to look like animal pelts strewn about.

Each "protein" is made up of 100 pelts, random walking around the canvas from the center. Each "pelt" is made of 5 colors sampled from an array of 84 colors.

Press 's' when in live view to save the image.

metadata.name: Until biodiversity rains #61
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. 

In the interpretation of biological organisms, which break paradigms by doing something different, to adapt to changes and be able to survive, paths emerge to be imitated by so many, and make life flow. The development of the work is a metaphor for those paths full of ingenuity and risk, where colorful organisms in rows open trails, sliding like subtle drops, with sophisticated turns and elastic jumps.

Some alternative paths usually hide a message along the way. Literally, one could find and read phrases in relation to biodiversity and its importance. Although it is more common to ignore them, sometimes not respect them, or what is worse, forget them. Even so, in an exacerbated insistence, here, audiovisual organizations seem to be repeating themselves, “until biodiversity rains”, and variety exploits so that ecosystems finally go it alone.


Relationship between visuals and sounds:
Biological organisms of different colors follow a path. They move forward, change shape, stop, turn. Always one after the other. At certain moments, they stretch and jump and sounds emerge.

Towards the edges of the canvas, the jumps are translated into cello sounds, mainly pizzicatos. Towards the center, the piano. From the main jumps emerges a kind of melody played by a pseudo-theremin-synth, characterized by flyaway melodies with glissant.


This artwork is 100% code, made in p5.js + tone.js.

[ Click ]  -> sound ON / OFF
[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ p ] -> pause / play 

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.
It is recommended to run the piece in a new window from the “open” button.

metadata.name: Mono Vibration #2
metadata.description:
It's a unique and captivating generative artwork, created with the aid of AI, which adds a touch of innovation and dynamism to the piece. This black and white, high-contrast artwork showcases the interplay of sin waves, moiré patterns, and Voronoi diagrams to create an engaging visual experience that stimulates the viewer's imagination.

The AI's creative input allows for the seamless integration of distinct visual elements and a dynamic composition that keeps the viewer's eyes moving across the canvas. Mono Vibration is a testament to the power of human-AI collaboration, blending the artist's vision with the AI's creative capabilities to produce a mesmerizing work of art that evokes a sense of depth, movement, and harmony.

metadata.name: Lookouts #66
metadata.description:
Lookouts is a generative illustration done 100% in code using p5js. Inspired by my love for travel and minimalist design, this collection is built based on custom shapes filled with solid colors & limited texture.

The accompanying fxtext article (in ‘Mentions’ below) shares more details about the inspiration and development process of this project.

Lookouts renders as a fixed resolution output (2000 x 1666px). Controls (in live view): 
Press [4] to render at 4000 x 3333px
Press [8] to render at 8000 x 6666px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)
